arly modern people saw verbal and visual texts as closely related, Susan Frye discusses the connections between the many forms of women's textualities, including notes in samplers, alphabets both stitched and penned, initials, ciphers, and extensive texts like needlework pictures, self-portraits, poetry, and pamphlets, as well as commissioned artwork, architecture, and interior design. She examines works on paper and cloth by such famous figures as Elizabeth I, Mary, Queen of Scots, and Bess of Hardwick, as well as the output of journeywomen needleworkers and miniaturists Levina Teerlinc and Esther Inglis, and their lesser-known sisters in the English colonies of the New World. Frye shows how traditional women's work was a way for women to communicate with one another and to shape their own identities within familial, intellectual, religious, and historical traditions. Pens and Needles offers insights into women's lives and into such literary texts as Shakespeare's Othello and Cymbeline and Mary Sidney Wroth's Urania.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArt and societyzEnglandxHistoryx16th century. 0aArt and societyzEnglandxHistoryx17th century. 0aArt and societyzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aArt and societyzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aArts and societyzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aArts and societyzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aArts, Englishx16th century. 0aArts, Englishx17th century. 0aMaterial culturexSocial aspectszEngland. 0aWomen and the artszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aWomen and the artszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aWomenzEnglandxSocial conditionsy16th century. 0aWomenzEnglandxSocial conditionsy17th century. 0aWomenzEnglandxSocial conditions. 4aArchitecture. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  